hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a very long, taut elastic string, one end of which is fixed at position $x=0$. The transverse displacement of the string, $u(x, t)$, for $x \ge 0$ and $t \ge 0$, is governed by the one-dimensional wave equation $u_{tt} = c^2 u_{xx}$, where the wave propagation speed is $c = 2.0$ m/s. The fixed end implies the boundary condition $u(0, t) = 0$ for all $t \ge 0$.

At time $t=0$, the string is held at rest, so its initial velocity is zero everywhere. The initial displacement of the string is given by a rectangular pulse of height $H=0.10$ m, located between $x=3.0$ m and $x=5.0$ m. Mathematically, the initial displacement is:
$$
u(x, 0) = f(x) =
\begin{cases}
H & \text{for } 3.0 \le x \le 5.0 \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$

Calculate the transverse displacement of the string at the position $x_0 = 1.0$ m and time $t_0 = 2.5$ s. Express your answer in meters, rounded to three significant figures.
